European banking contagion weighs on U.S. particularly the endless Credit Suisse saga. As usual, waiting for results of the Silicon Valley bank auction. And seeing which bank needs to start raising equity to match the mismatch of held to maturity long paper and deposit flight

We are never going to be able to protect banks that have highly concentrated deposit bases when a couple of big depositors flee. Or we would never have had such a decline in First Republic's stock. Enough until the a.m. or whenever

Protect all or protect  none but just $JPM, $WFC, and $BAC. Those are the only banks that cash managers will not get fired for if they put in more then $250,000. That's what last week did and an anonymous pledge does not cut it.

So, until this is all resolved in a way that all have insurance for all deposits at a much higher amount if not infinite, the big banks will win and we will end up like Europe. Bad, discriminatory doctrine

Most important we now have two clashing doctrines: no one bank should be bigger than ten percent but not all banks are "insured" equally because the big banks have the best deposit base and are the most tightly regulated
No corporate treasurer wants to have to check to see a bank's held-to- maturity bond book before it puts $1million in overnight knowing that any noisy exiting depositor could bring down the house

Two doctrines: no one bank should have more than 10% of the country's deposits and we only insure up to $250,000 at each bank. A fiduciary after last week has to put no more than $250,000 in any one bank except the biggest, most regulated bank...

Here's the problem as I see it: if you are in charge of a cash management program as i once was I would feel compelled to take more than $250,000 out of any bank. I can not count on the word of an anonymous Treasury official. That's nonsense.

FDIC has to allow the JPMorgan loan to First Republic be back stop and be converted to equity if necessary. Just trying to put out some solutions that could help us through this
Schwab's defense seemed logical and i think that Citigroup has a similar group of depositors that are strong but invisible to the typical screen... but those two really worried people

So FDIC must do an extension to cover $500,000 in deposits and it must allow a one-time purchase of failing/failed banks by the concentrated powerful banks.. or this drags on... Infusions of capital won't work as this is all confidence based not equity based
So the FDIC is relying on a ragtag bunch of PE firms and smaller regionals like PNC which, themselves are under attack

I am sure, for example,  if you could get the FDIC to put a bank in receivership and then let a BAC or a JPM or a WFC to buy their assets and liabilities with IMMUNITY, then you end the crisis. But they won't.
Why is it so hard to get stability in the banking stocks? Because the banks that know how to buy are considered too big to be allowed to buy

The issue with the banking system is a lack of confidence, not lack of equity. You get a real auction by the FDIC, which, unfortunately is a novice at this, for Silicon Valley Bank, one that succeeds and this nightmare may be over
